[ProMED thanks Mahmoud Orabi for this submission.

_Listeria monocytogenes_, the cause of listeriosis, is widely distributed in nature. The organism is a Gram-positive bacillus that can be found in soil, water, silage, raw vegetables, raw meat and poultry, raw (unpasteurized) milk, soft cheeses, kitchen premises used to process contaminated meat or fish and vegetables, and in the intestinal tract of many animals, including cattle, sheep, humans, crustaceans, fish, shellfish, ticks, and insects. Most human infections are foodborne, although vertical transmission can occur from mother to fetus transplacentally or during delivery through an infected birth canal, and localized skin infections can occur in veterinarians and farmers by direct contact with infected animals.

Contamination of food can occur in nature (e.g., raw vegetables contaminated by soil and manure, and raw milk and cheese made from raw milk by infected cows), or contamination can occur after cooking or other processing.

Even if the initial contamination adds only a few _Listeria_ organisms to the food, the contamination can become significant for refrigerated foods because _L. monocytogenes_ can multiply at refrigerator temperatures to a sufficient number to cause disease when the food is ingested. Thus, it is not surprising that listeriosis is usually associated with ingestion of contaminated raw milk and cheese made from raw milk, as well as ready-to-eat (RTE) meat or vegetable products that have been held at refrigeration temperatures. _Listeria_ can also survive in frozen food. Consumption of raw milk, raw-milk soft cheeses (e.g., brie, camembert, and Mexican soft cheeses), coleslaw, raw vegetables in salads, pate, deli cold cut meats, hotdogs, and raw or undercooked seafood, e.g., smoked or cured salmon, oysters, or sushi (https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2020/10/201007123057.htm) have been sources of human listeriosis.

The sources of human infection can be pinpointed by molecular techniques, i.e., matching genotypes of _Listeria_ isolated from patients with genotypes of _Listeria_ isolated from a possible source.

People aged 65 years or older and those with an impaired immune system are at increased risk for listeriosis. Due to pregnancy-related immunosuppression, pregnant women are 10 or more times more likely to get listeriosis than the general population (https://www.acog.org/clinical/clinical-guidance/committee-opinion/articles/2014/12/management-of-pregnant-women-with-presumptive-exposure-to-listeria-monocytogenes). However, many pregnant women may have no symptoms or only mild illness, with fever, myalgia, backache, and headache, often accompanied by diarrhea or other gastrointestinal symptoms. Nevertheless, fetal and neonatal infection can be severe and potentially fatal. The pregnancy may terminate in miscarriage, stillbirth, or preterm labor, and the infection in the neonate can result in sepsis or meningitis.

People at increased risk for disseminated listeriosis, which include pregnant women, should avoid eating food potentially contaminated with _Listeria_. Proper food handling, in particular separating uncooked meats or fish from other items during preparation and washing hands, utensils, and cutting boards after handling uncooked foods, is critical. Adequate treatment of an exposed pregnant woman with fever and signs and symptoms consistent with listeriosis for whom no other cause of illness is known should be tested and treated for presumptive listeriosis; no testing, including blood and stool cultures, or treatment is indicated for an asymptomatic pregnant woman who reports consumption of a product that was recalled or implicated during an outbreak of _Listeria_ contamination, according to guidance from the American College of Obstetrics and Gynecology (https://www.acog.org/clinical/clinical-guidance/committee-opinion/articles/2014/12/management-of-pregnant-women-with-presumptive-exposure-to-listeria-monocytogenes). The article goes on to say: "A pregnant woman who ate a product that was recalled because of _Listeria_ contamination and who is afebrile but has signs and symptoms consistent with a minor gastrointestinal or flu-like illness can be managed expectantly."
(https://www.acog.org/clinical/clinical-guidance/committee-opinion/articles/2014/12/management-of-pregnant-women-with-presumptive-exposure-to-listeria-monocytogenes)

Ampicillin, alone or in combination with gentamicin, is the 1st line of treatment; trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole is an alternative but should be avoided in the 1st trimester of pregnancy because of its antifolate effect, associated with neural tube defects (https://www.cdc.gov/pregnancy/meds/treatingfortwo/features/kf-uti-antibiotic-treatments-pregnant-women.html). - Mod.ML

